## 2. `merge_pair()` - Merging the Selected Pair Throughout Corpus

### Purpose
Replace every occurrence of the specific adjacent token pair with a single merged token.

### Detailed Implementation Strategy

```c
void merge_pair(Sentence corpus[], int corpus_size, char* best_left, char* best_right) {
    // Create the merged token by concatenating
    char merged_token[MAX_TOKEN_LEN];
    strcpy(merged_token, best_left);
    strcat(merged_token, best_right);

    // Process each sentence
    for (int sent_idx = 0; sent_idx < corpus_size; sent_idx++) {
        Sentence *sentence = &corpus[sent_idx];

        // Scan from left to right, looking for the pair
        int i = 0;
        while (i < sentence->token_count - 1) {
            // Check if current position has the target pair
            if (strcmp(sentence->tokens[i], best_left) == 0 &&
                strcmp(sentence->tokens[i + 1], best_right) == 0) {

                // MERGE: Replace first token with merged version
                strcpy(sentence->tokens[i], merged_token);

                // SHIFT: Move all tokens after position i+1 to the left by 1
                for (int j = i + 1; j < sentence->token_count - 1; j++) {
                    strcpy(sentence->tokens[j], sentence->tokens[j + 1]);
                }

                // Update token count (we removed one token)
                sentence->token_count--;

                // DON'T increment i - we might have created a new mergeable pair
                // at the same position
            } else {
                i++; // Only advance if no merge happened
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Details:
- **In-place modification**: We modify the corpus array directly
- **Careful indexing**: After a merge, don't immediately advance `i` because the merged token might create new mergeable pairs
- **String operations**: Use `strcpy` and `strcat` for string manipulation
- **Array shifting**: When removing a token, shift all subsequent tokens left

