## 4. `greedy_bpe_tokenize()` - Tokenizing Input with Longest Match

### Purpose
Take a new input sentence and tokenize it using the trained BPE vocabulary with greedy longest-match strategy.

### Detailed Implementation Strategy

```c
void greedy_bpe_tokenize(char *input, Dictionary *token_to_id) {
    // Split input into words
    char input_copy[MAX_LINE_LEN];
    strcpy(input_copy, input);

    char *word = strtok(input_copy, " \t\n");

    while (word != NULL) {
        printf("Word '%s': ", word);

        // Add end-of-word marker
        char word_with_end[MAX_TOKEN_LEN];
        strcpy(word_with_end, word);
        strcat(word_with_end, "</w>");

        int pos = 0;
        int word_len = strlen(word_with_end);

        // Greedy longest-match tokenization
        while (pos < word_len) {
            int best_match_len = 0;
            char best_match[MAX_TOKEN_LEN];
            KVPair *best_kv = NULL;

            // Try all possible prefixes starting from current position
            // Start with longest possible and work down
            for (int len = word_len - pos; len >= 1; len--) {
                char candidate[MAX_TOKEN_LEN];
                strncpy(candidate, word_with_end + pos, len);
                candidate[len] = '\0';

                // Check if this candidate exists in vocabulary
                KVPair *kv = dictionary_find(token_to_id, candidate);
                if (kv != NULL) {
                    // Found a match! Since we start with longest, this is optimal
                    best_match_len = len;
                    strcpy(best_match, candidate);
                    best_kv = kv;
                    break; // Take first (longest) match
                }
            }

            if (best_match_len > 0) {
                // Found a token in vocabulary
                printf("[%s -> %s] ", best_match, (char*)best_kv->value);
                pos += best_match_len;
            } else {
                // No match found - treat as unknown character
                char unk_char[2] = {word_with_end[pos], '\0'};
                printf("[UNK(%s)] ", unk_char);
                pos++; // Move forward by 1 character
            }
        }

        printf("\n");
        word = strtok(NULL, " \t\n");
    }
}
```

### Key Details:
- **Longest-first strategy**: Try longest possible substrings first, work down to single characters
- **End-of-word handling**: Always append `</w>` to each word before tokenizing
- **Unknown characters**: If no vocabulary match exists, output `[UNK(character)]`
- **Output format**: Must match exactly: `Word 'wordname': [token -> id] [token -> id] ...`
- **Greedy property**: Once you find a match, take it and move to the next position

